An '''''échevin'''''{{refn|group=n|Sometimes also [[anglicization|anglicized]] as '''eschevin'''. A French derivation from the medieval office of ''[[Échevin (disambiguation)|scabinus]]''. The equivalent office in southern France was known as a "consul".}} ({{lang-lb|Schäffe}}; {{lang-de|Schöffe}}), sometimes translated as '''[[alderman]]''',{{refn|group=n|As in a bilingual letter sent from the London embassy to Luxembourger nationals residing in the UK.{{fact|date=January 2016}}}} is a member of the administration of a [[Luxembourg]]ian [[Communes of Luxembourg|commune]].  Together, they form the ''collège échevinal'' ({{lang-de|Schöffenrat}}), which helps the [[mayor]] run the administration.  In most communes, ''échevins'' have designated roles within the administration, adopting separate briefs as in a [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]].

''Échevins'' are elected by the commune's council, and represent the make-up of the governing [[coalition]].  Formally, ''échevins'' of [[List of cities in Luxembourg|cities]] are named by the [[Grand Duke of Luxembourg|Grand Duke]], whilst those of other communes are named by the [[Minister for the Interior of Luxembourg|Minister for the Interior]].  ''Échevins'' must be members of the communal council and hold Luxembourgian nationality.

Most communes have two ''échevins'', but more-populous ones are allowed more if granted that right by [[Grand Ducal decree]]: communes with 10,000 to 19,999 inhabitants may have 3 ''échevins'', communes with 20,000 or more may have 4 ''échevins'', and [[Luxembourg City]] may have up to six.

